            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Treatise originally addressed to Ibn ʿArabī’s friend in Tunis, al-Mahdawī, describing the way in which the soul is educated and advised by the Holy Spirit through the example of previous generations, present-day masters and by direct inspiration. The middle section, describing his early education with over 70 teachers in Spain and North Africa, was translated by R W J Austin in the 1970s and published as Sufis of Andalusia (London, 1971); it has subsequently become one of the best known texts by IA in modern times.</note>
               <note type="biblioComments">A much copied work, verified by three historic mss. The best is undoubtedly University A79 which is in the hand of SQ’s father and is the riwāya (transmission) of al-Ḥabashī, dated 600H, with at least nine samāʿs in IA’s lifetime.</note>
